#: ../../source/fundamentals/lifecycle-events.rst:2
msgid "Lifecycle Events"
msgstr "Lifecycle Events"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/lifecycle-events.rst:4
msgid ""
"Every application element has a lifecycle managed by Nest. Nest offers "
"**lifecycle hooks** that provide visibility into key life moments and the"
" ability to act when they occur."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/lifecycle-events.rst:9
msgid "Lifecycle sequence"
msgstr "Lifecycle sequence"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/lifecycle-events.rst:11
msgid ""
"After creating a injectable/controller by calling its constructor, Nest "
"calls the lifecycle hook methods in the following sequence at specific "
"moments:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/lifecycle-events.rst:16
msgid "``OnModuleIn it``"
msgstr "``OnModuleIn it``"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/lifecycle-events.rst:16
msgid "Called once the host module has been initialized"
msgstr "Called once the host module has been initialized"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/lifecycle-events.rst:19
msgid "``OnApplicat ionBootstrap ``"
msgstr "``OnApplicat ionBootstrap ``"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/lifecycle-events.rst:19
msgid "Called once the application has fully started and is bootstrapped"
msgstr "Called once the application has fully started and is bootstrapped"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/lifecycle-events.rst:23
msgid "``OnModuleDe stroy``"
msgstr "``OnModuleDe stroy``"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/lifecycle-events.rst:23
msgid ""
"Cleanup just before Nest destroys the host module (``app.close()`` method"
" has been evaluated)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/lifecycle-events.rst:26
msgid "``OnApplicat ionShutdown` `"
msgstr "``OnApplicat ionShutdown` `"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/lifecycle-events.rst:26
msgid ""
"Responds to the system signals (when application gets shutdown by e.g. \\"
" ``SIGTERM``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/lifecycle-events.rst:32
#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:131
msgid "Usage"
msgstr "Usage"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/lifecycle-events.rst:34
msgid ""
"Each lifecycle hook is represented by interface. Interfaces are "
"technically optional because they do not exist anyway after TypeScript "
"compilation. Nonetheless, it’s a good practice to use them in order to "
"benefit from strong typing and editor tooling."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/lifecycle-events.rst:60
msgid ""
"Additionally, both ``OnModuleInit`` and ``OnApplicationBootstrap`` hooks "
"allow you to defer the application initialization process (return a "
"``Promise`` or mark the method as ``async``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/lifecycle-events.rst:76
msgid "OnApplicationShutdown"
msgstr "OnApplicationShutdown"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/lifecycle-events.rst:78
msgid ""
"The ``OnApplicationShutdown`` responds to the system signals (when "
"application gets shutdown by e.g. \\ ``SIGTERM``). Use this hook to "
"gracefully shutdown a Nest application. This feature is often used with "
"`Kubernetes <https://kubernetes.io/>`__, `Heroku "
"<https://www.heroku.com/>`__ or similar services."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/lifecycle-events.rst:84
msgid ""
"To use this hook you must activate a listener which listens to shutdown "
"signals."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/lifecycle-events.rst:100
msgid ""
"If the application receives a signal it will call the "
"``onApplicationShutdown`` function of your ``Injectable`` with the "
"corresponding signal as first parameter. If your function does return a "
"promise, it will not shutdown your Nest application until the promise is "
"resolved or rejected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/platform-agnosticism.rst:2
msgid "Platform agnosticism"
msgstr "Platform agnosticism"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/platform-agnosticism.rst:4
msgid ""
"The whole point of Nest is staying as a platform-agnostic framework. A "
"platform independence makes possible creating **reusable logical parts**,"
" that people can take advantage of across several different types of "
"applications. A framework’s architecture is focused on being applicable "
"to any kind of server-side solution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/platform-agnosticism.rst:11
msgid "Build once, use everywhere"
msgstr "Build once, use everywhere"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/platform-agnosticism.rst:13
msgid ""
"An **overview** category is mostly referring to HTTP server (REST APIs). "
"However, all those building blocks can be easily used in different "
"transport layers (``microservices`` or ``websockets`` packages). "
"Furthermore, Nest comes with a dedicated `GraphQL </graphql/quick-"
"start>`__ module. Last but not least, an `application context "
"</application-context>`__ feature helps to create everything that runs on"
" Node.js on top of Nest."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/platform-agnosticism.rst:21
msgid ""
"Nest inspires to be a fully-fledged platform, that brings a higher-level "
"of reusability for your applications. Build once, use everywhere!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:2
msgid "Injection scopes"
msgstr "Injection scopes"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:4
msgid ""
"For the people coming from different languages, it might be awkward that "
"in Nest almost everything is shared across the incoming requests. We have"
" a connection pool to the database, singleton services with a global "
"state etc. Generally, Node.js doesn’t follow request/response Multi-"
"Threaded Stateless Model in which every request is being processed by the"
" separate thread. Hence, using singleton instances is fully **safe** for "
"our applications."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:12
msgid ""
"However, there are edge-cases when request-based lifetime of the "
"controller may be an intentional behavior, for instance per-request cache"
" in GraphQL applications, request tracking or multi-tenancy. How can we "
"handle them?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:18
msgid "Scopes"
msgstr "Scopes"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:20
msgid ""
"Basically, every provider can act as a singleton, be request-scoped, and "
"be switched to the transient mode. See the following table to get "
"familiar with the differences between them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:36
msgid "SINGLETON"
msgstr "SINGLETON"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:46
msgid ""
"Each provider can be shared across multiple classes. The provider "
"lifetime is strictly tied to the application lifecycle. Once the "
"application has bootstrapped, all providers are already instantiated. The"
" singleton scope is being used by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:67
msgid "REQUEST"
msgstr "REQUEST"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:77
msgid ""
"A new instance of the provider is going to be exclusively created for "
"every incoming request and garbage collected after the request processing"
" is completed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:97
msgid "TRANSIENT"
msgstr "TRANSIENT"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:107
msgid ""
"Transient providers cannot be shared between providers. Every time when "
"another provider asks the Nest container for particular transient "
"provider, the container will create a new, dedicated instance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:125
msgid ""
"info **Hint** Using a singleton scope is always the **recommended** way. "
"Sharing providers among requests leads to lower memory consumption and "
"thus to better performance of your application (no requirement to "
"instantiate class every time)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:133
msgid ""
"In order to switch to another injection scope, you have to pass an "
"argument to the ``@Injectable()`` decorator:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:143
msgid ""
"In the case of `custom providers </fundamentals/custom-providers>`__, you"
" have to set an extra ``scope`` property:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:154
msgid "And when it comes to controllers, pass the ``ControllerOptions`` object:"
msgstr "And when it comes to controllers, pass the ``ControllerOptions`` object:"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:166
msgid ""
"warning **Notice** Gateways should never rely on request-scoped providers"
" because they act as singletons. One gateway encapsulates a real socket "
"inside and cannot be instantiated multiple times."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:171
msgid "Per-request injection"
msgstr "Per-request injection"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:173
msgid ""
"The request-scoped providers have to be used very carefully. Keep in mind"
" that the scope actually bubbles up in the **injection chain**. If your "
"controller depends on a provider which is request-scoped, it means that "
"your controller is actually request-scoped as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:178
msgid ""
"Imagine the following chain: ``CatsController <- CatsService <- "
"CatsRepository``. If your ``CatsService`` is request-scoped (and the rest"
" are, theoretically, singletons), the ``CatsController`` would become "
"request-scoped too (because request-scoped instance have to be injected "
"into a newly created controller), whereas ``CatsRepository`` would remain"
" as a singleton."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:186
msgid ""
"**Warning** The circular dependencies in this case will lead to very "
"painful side-effects and thus, you should certainly avoid creating them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:191
msgid "Request provider"
msgstr "Request provider"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:193
msgid ""
"In the HTTP application, using request-scoped providers gives you a "
"capability to inject an original request reference."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:207
msgid ""
"However, this functionality doesn’t work with either micro services or "
"GraphQL applications. In `GraphQL </graphql/quick-start>`__ applications,"
" you can inject ``CONTEXT`` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:221
msgid ""
"Afterwards, you can configure your ``context`` value (in the "
"``GraphQLModule``) to contain ``request`` as its property."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:225
msgid "Performance"
msgstr "Performance"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/provider-scopes.rst:227
msgid ""
"Using request-scoped providers will obviously affect application "
"performance. Even though Nest is trying to cache as much metadata as "
"possible, it will still have to create an instance of your class on each "
"request. Hence, it will slow down your average response time and overall "
"benchmarking result. If your provider doesn’t necessarily need to be "
"request-scoped, you should rather stick with the singleton scope."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/unit-testing.rst:2
msgid "Testing"
msgstr "Testing"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/unit-testing.rst:4
msgid ""
"Automatic tests are an essential part of the fully functional **software "
"product**. That is very critical to cover at least the most sensitive "
"parts of your system. In order to accomplish that goal, we produce a set "
"of different tests like integration tests, unit tests, e2e tests, and so "
"on. And Nest provides a bunch of test utilities that improves testing "
"experience."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/unit-testing.rst:11
msgid ""
"In general, you can use any **testing framework** that you enjoy working "
"with. We don’t enforce tooling, choose whatever fits your requirements. "
"The main Nest application starter is integrated with `Jest "
"<https://github.com/facebook/jest>`__ framework to reduce an amount of "
"overhead when it comes to start writing your tests, but still, you can "
"get rid of it and use any other tool easily."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/unit-testing.rst:19
msgid "Installation"
msgstr "Installation"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/unit-testing.rst:21
msgid "Firstly, we need to install the required package:"
msgstr "Firstly, we need to install the required package:"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/unit-testing.rst:28
msgid "Unit testing"
msgstr "Unit testing"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/unit-testing.rst:30
msgid ""
"In the following example, we have two different classes, "
"``CatsController`` and ``CatsService`` respectively. As mentioned before,"
" `Jest <https://github.com/facebook/jest>`__ is used as a fully-fledged "
"testing framework. That framework behaves like a test-runner and also, "
"provides assert functions and test-doubles utilities that helps with "
"mocking, spying, etc. We have manually enforced ``catsService.findAll()``"
" method to return ``result`` variable, once it’s called. Thanks to that, "
"we can test whether ``catsController.findAll()`` returns expected result,"
" or not."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/unit-testing.rst:89
msgid ""
"info **Hint** Keep your test files nearby tested classes. The testing "
"files should have a ``.spec`` or ``.test`` suffix."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/unit-testing.rst:92
msgid ""
"We didn’t make use of any existing Nest testing utility so far. Since we "
"have manually taken care of instantiating tested classes, above test "
"suite has nothing to do with Nest. This type of testing is called "
"**isolated tests**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/unit-testing.rst:98
msgid "Testing utilities"
msgstr "Testing utilities"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/unit-testing.rst:100
msgid ""
"The ``@nestjs/testing`` package gives us a set of utilities that boost "
"the testing process. Let’s rewrite the previous example, but now, using "
"exposed ``Test`` class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/unit-testing.rst:163
msgid ""
"``Test`` class has a ``createTestingModule()`` method that takes a module"
" metadata (the same object as this one passed in ``@Module()`` decorator)"
" as an argument. This method creates a ``TestingModule`` instance which "
"in turn provides a few methods, but only one of them is useful when it "
"comes to unit tests - the ``compile()``. This function is "
"**asynchronous**, therefore it has to be awaited. Once module is "
"compiled, you can retrieve any instance using ``get()`` method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/unit-testing.rst:171
msgid ""
"In order to mock a real instance, you can override existing provider with"
" a `custom provider </fundamentals/dependency-injection>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/unit-testing.rst:175
msgid "End-to-end testing"
msgstr "End-to-end testing"

#: ../../source/fundamentals/unit-testing.rst:177
msgid ""
"When the application grows, it is hard to manually test a behavior of "
"each API endpoint. The end-to-end tests help us to make sure that "
"everything is working correctly and fits project requirements. To perform"
" e2e tests we use the same configuration as in the case of **unit "
"testing**, but additionally, we take advantage of `supertest "
"<https://github.com/visionmedia/supertest>`__ library that allows "
"simulating HTTP requests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/unit-testing.rst:262
msgid ""
"info **Hint** Keep your e2e test files inside the ``e2e`` directory. The "
"testing files should have a ``.e2e-spec`` or ``.e2e-test`` suffix."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/fundamentals/unit-testing.rst:266
msgid ""
"The ``cats.e2e-spec.ts`` test file contains a single HTTP endpoint test "
"(``/cats``). We have used ``app.getHttpServer()`` method to pick up an "
"underlying HTTP server that runs in the background of Nest application. "
"Notice that ``TestingModule`` instance provides a ``overrideProvider()`` "
"method, and thus we can **override** the existing provider which is "
"declared by the imported module. Also, we can successively override the "
"guards, interceptors, filters, and pipes using corresponding methods, "
"``overrideGuard()``, ``overrideInterceptor()``, ``overrideFilter()``, and"
" ``overridePipe()`` respectively."
msgstr ""

